<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="70" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1362,1645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1362,1387]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Remarks</emphasis>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Stackelberg" box="[485,701,1362,1387]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" refString="Stackelberg, A. A. (1934) Dolichopodidae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der Palaearktischen Region, 82, 129 - 176." type="journal article" year="1934">Stackelberg (1934)</bibRefCitation>
the new species is included in the third group of 
<taxonomicName box="[1289,1436,1363,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hercostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1289,1436,1363,1386]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Hercostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(femora yellow, postocular setae black). In the key to Palaearctic species (Selivanova 
<emphasis box="[1116,1165,1398,1422]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">et al</emphasis>
. 2012), the new species runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Becker, 1922" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1922" box="[244,686,1434,1459]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hercostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="congruens">
<emphasis box="[244,519,1435,1458]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Hercostomus congruens</emphasis>
Becker, 1922
</taxonomicName>
, which is known from the Palaearctic and Oriental regions and belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[393,558,1471,1494]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Gymnopternus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[393,558,1471,1494]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Gymnopternus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Becker, 1922" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1922" box="[1074,1399,1470,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hercostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="congruens">
<emphasis box="[1074,1223,1471,1494]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">G. congruens</emphasis>
(Becker, 1922)
</taxonomicName>
by the following features: the latter species has a cluster of fine setulae in front of the posterior spiracle and R4+5 and M1+2 are parallel distally. In the key to Chinese species (
<bibRefCitation author="Yang" box="[795,990,1545,1570]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" refString="Yang, D., Zhang, L., Wang, M. &amp; Zhu, Y. (2011) Dolichopodidae. Fauna Sinica. Insecta 53. Beijing. Science Press, 1912 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Yang 
<emphasis box="[864,915,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
), the new species runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Yang, 1997" authorityName="Yang" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hercostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wudangshanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Hercostomus wudangshanus</emphasis>
Yang, 1997
</taxonomicName>
and can be distinguished from the latter by the morphology of hypopygium and the following characters:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1435,1692,1772]" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
- Antennae black. Stylus dorsal. Postpedicel without apical incision. Hind femur yellow.... 
<taxonomicName authority="Yang" authorityName="Yang" box="[1106,1433,1692,1713]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hercostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wudangshanus">
<emphasis box="[1106,1379,1692,1713]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Hercostomus wudangshanus</emphasis>
Yang
</taxonomicName>
